## Content Transformation Examples

### Example 1: Journal Entry → Blog Post

**Input** (from journal):
> "While I was working out today, I realized that both Postman and Planton have same number of characters and also start and end with the same letter. That is a legit coincidence."

**Output** (blog post opening):
> I've been thinking a lot about Postman lately. It's the only developer tool company that truly came out of India and earned global love from the tech community. I'm determined to make Planton the second one.
> 
> ## A Curious Coincidence
> 
> Today during my workout, something clicked: both Postman and Planton have exactly 7 characters. They both start with 'P' and end with 'N'. Pure coincidence, but it feels like a good omen.

### Example 2: Conversation → Blog Post

**Input** (technical discovery):
> "I just realized our current system doesn't support target-cluster references in kubernetes-components anymore. But there's more standardization now for kubernetes-based components."

**Output** (blog post structure):
> When you're deep in building a platform, sometimes the best insights come from recognizing what you can remove, not what you can add.
> 
> ## The Abstraction Trap
> 
> For the longest time, our system tried to abstract away Kubernetes namespaces. We thought we were helping users by handling namespace creation automatically. [...]
> 
> ## The Shift to Simplicity
> 
> Today I realized we don't need target-cluster references anymore. [...]

